05523nam a22007575i 9780824860714DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20102011hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248607147 a10.1515/97808248607142doi  a(DE-B1597)484200  a(OCoLC)1024029913  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aGV1102.7.R44bB67 2011eb 7aHIS0080002bisacsh04a796.815 52221 aBoretz, Avron, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGods, Ghosts, and Gangsters :bRitual Violence, Martial Arts, and Masculinity on the Margins of Chinese Society /cAvron Boretz. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2010] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b15 b&w illustrations, 2 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Translation and Use of Foreign Terms -- tChapter 1. Introduction -- tChapter 2. Violence, Honor, and Manhood -- tChapter 3. Taidong: The Mountains and Beyond -- tChapter 4. Fire and Fury -- tChapter 5. Tales from the Jianghu -- tChapter 6. Wine, Women, and Song -- tChapter 7. Conclusion: Faces of the Gods -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDemon warrior puppets, sword-wielding Taoist priests, spirit mediums lacerating their bodies with spikes and blades—these are among the most dramatic images in Chinese religion. Usually linked to the propitiation of plague gods and the worship of popular military deities, such ritual practices have an obvious but previously unexamined kinship with the traditional Chinese martial arts.The long and durable history of martial arts iconography and ritual in Chinese religion suggests something far deeper than mere historical coincidence. Avron Boretz argues that martial arts gestures and movements are so deeply embedded in the ritual repertoire in part because they iconify masculine qualities of violence, aggressivity, and physical prowess, the implicit core of Chinese patriliny and patriarchy. At the same time, for actors and audience alike, martial arts gestures evoke the mythos of the jianghu, a shadowy, often violent realm of vagabonds, outlaws, and masters of martial and magic arts. Through the direct bodily practice of martial arts movement and creative rendering of jianghu narratives, martial ritual practitioners are able to identify and represent themselves, however briefly and incompletely, as men of prowess, a reward otherwise denied those confined to the lower limits of this deeply patriarchal society.Based on fieldwork in China and Taiwan spanning nearly two decades, Gods, Ghosts, and Gangsters offers a thorough and original account of violent ritual and ritual violence in Chinese religion and society. Close-up, sensitive portrayals and the voices of ritual actors themselves—mostly working-class men, many of them members of sworn brotherhoods and gangs—convincingly link martial ritual practice to the lives and desires of men on the margins of Chinese society. This work is a significant contribution to the study of Chinese ritual and religion, the history and sociology of Chinese underworld, the history and anthropology of the martial arts, and the anthropology of masculinity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aMartial artszChinaxReligious aspects. 0aMartial artszTaiwanxReligious aspects. 0aMasculinityzChina. 0aMasculinityzTaiwan. 0aViolencezChinaxReligious aspects. 0aViolencezTaiwanxReligious aspects. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000